Prepare to be underwhelmed by the decor and astonished by the food; Oshi's spare, neo-brutalist dining area doesn't do their dishes justice. But you can't eat ambiance, can you?  All dishes are made to order and while you watch, so if you order their Rock bowl, be patient; they don't start making the fried shrimp until you order it. It's worth waiting for, as they come out piping hot and crispy. Try The Rock with squid-ink rice and arugula as your base, and prepare for the spicy togarashi sauce with peanuts; it's easily a two-beer dish.  Draft Asahi beer is available, as is chilled sake and soda. There are lots of exotic drinks in the chiller, and American sodas in the self-serve.  This is a great place to go for something different; you'll want to be a regular.
Best Poke in town!  Ingredients are fresh and plentiful. Many options for build your own poke bowl and several delicious recipes created to select.

I was in Huntsville last week on a business trip and wanted to try a new place so I went here for lunch (take out). I ordered a Build Your Own Poke Bowl with sushi rice, little spinach, scallions and salmon - I wanted to build something that resembles Chirashi-Zushi. It costs $14 which I thought was little expensive since they only give you a “scoop” of chopped salmon.  Their sushi rice was pretty good and salmon was very fresh. Overall, it wasn’t a bad poke bowl but wasn’t anything exceptional (I had to ask for Wasabi since they don’t just offer you). My hotel was near by and poke bowl wasn’t bad so I went back for dinner (take out again). I wanted something simple so I got tuna, salmon and yellowtail rolls.  Once again, all the fish was fresh and delicious, and sushi rice was good.  But something about them was not 100% right - maybe it was Nori or the way they were rolled or something.  That’s why I give it 3 stars.

The owner was such a pleasure to talk to she made her way to each table talking to the patrons. She even gave us some insight on living in Huntsville since we were considering a move to town.  We will definitely be coming back when in town.

So fantastic! The food was so amazing and “light”. Very filling due to the large portions but I didn’t feel bad from eating it all. Super healthy options! The food and quality were outstanding! I had a build-your-own bowl, with brown rice and spinach. The edamame was fresh and flavorful, and the multiple sauce options were delightful. Not overly expensive, but too much to make it a daily fix. The staff was immensely helpful and accommodating, and tlrounded out a wonderful lunch date with my daughter. I don't know her name, as she didn't have a name tag, so for this review we'll say her name is "Shannon" my apologies if there is in fact an employee at Oshi Poke named Shannon who is a delightful person that is good at her job, this is not intended for you...just go in and look for the dark haired girl who looks as though she can make puppies explode with an icey stare... that's "Shannon" This was our first visit to Oshi and we were unsure what to order. I tried to break the ice with Shannon and admitted to being first timers and not having a clue what to order...I then asked Shannon for a suggestion...not a kidney..a suggestion. Shannon was quite apathetic with a faint whif of liberal arts degree. My concern is this is the face of your establishment...and she has the personality of an arthritic game of thump knuckles. The rest of the staff was at least amicable. The sushi chef didn't say anything, but at least he gave alittle smile. We were not the only patrons given this treatment from Shannon...she doesn't seem to like people very much... especially people in the market for raw fish...which would be a conflict of interest at a sushi joint. Perchance "Shannon" would be better suited in another field of work...like if a personality factory had a horrific overflow of the personality tanks, Shannon could act as a human shamwow, and come in and soak all the excess personality. I'm not saying fire her, maybe it was an off night for Shannon...but if this is a hibitual habit, let's look at dish duty.

All in all, I think the food was good and the prices were fair, would eat lunch here again.

This place is a product of the gentrification of downtown Huntsville. The sushi is decent, the poke is not bad, but the price doesn't quite match the quality. It's like the Target of sushi and poké. If you're in the mood to spend more than you should, but still want to feel good about yourself when you leave, this place is for you.  Edit: I went back to try it again because I heard that they had ramen, so I figured I'd give them a second shot. Well, it is the sheer lack of quality of the ramen that has caused me to actually remove another star from this review. The only reason I won't give them just one star is because they are technically better than the dried and over-salted 10/$1 ramen that you can buy at any grocery store.  Now as for the specifics on  their ramen, the broth is too salty, the pork is dry, and the total absence of seaweed and egg makes the whole dish feel unauthentic. Even excusing all of that, the worst crime is that the noodles are pretty much the same quality or worse than store bought "ramen." They absorb the broth far too quickly and very soon you find yourself eating mush. Unless you're trying to get your date to ask you to take them home, don't bother with this place. I won't return willingly any time soon.
